laboratory_examinations.findings: Initial blood glucose level of 4 mg/dL (0.2 mmol/L) at 1 hour after birth, normalized after intravenous fluids. On admission, blood glucose was 182 mg/dL (10.1 mmol/L; reference range 70-106 mg/dL). Following a fast, blood glucose was found to be 39 mg/dL (2.2 mmol/L), decreased to 13 mg/dL (0.7 mmol/L) after glucagon administration.
laboratory_examinations.changes_over_time: Decreased blood glucose levels during fasting episodes, with initial normalization after feeding. Significant hypoglycemia occurred after a 6-hour fast.

laboratory_examinations.findings: WBC count of 20,300 per cubic millimeter (reference range 5,500 to 18,000).
Anion gap of 26 millimoles per liter (reference range 3 to 11) on presentation.
Bicarbonate level was 9 mmol per liter (reference range 21 to 32).
Plasma sodium of 134 mmol/L; potassium elevated at 7.9 mmol/L; calcium at 11.6 mg/dL; creatinine remained at 0.26 mg/dL.
laboratory_examinations.changes_over_time: Previous potassium level was normal, indicating acute elevation possibly due to sample hemolysis.

laboratory_examinations.findings: Clear, colorless urine with specific gravity of 1.005 and pH of 6.0; ketones were absent.
Insulin level of 6.0 μIU/mL (reference range 2.6 to 25.0), noted to be hemolyzed.
laboratory_examinations.changes_over_time: A subsequent test showed a repeat insulin level of <0.2 μIU/mL during another episode of hypoglycemia.

laboratory_examinations.findings: Lactic acid measured at 8.0 mmol per liter initially, later decreased to 6.1 mmol per liter.
Initial level of 1.1 mmol per liter (reference <0.4).
Triglyceride level at 1723 mg/dL (reference range 40 to 150).
Blood pyruvate level was elevated at 0.44 mmol/L (reference range 0.08 to 0.16).
Elevated uric acid at 7.1 mg/dL (reference range 2.0 to 5.5).
